Bring 2 large #saucepans{} of @water{for boiling} to the boil with @salt{0.25%tsp} in each (one for the potatoes, one for the celeriac). Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pour a large glug of @oil{} into a large #roasting tray{}. Pop it onto the top shelf of your oven to warm up. Peel the @potatoes{900%g} and chop into 4cm chunks. Add them to one of the pans of boiling water and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife. Meanwhile, pull the @rosemary{1}(leaves pulled off and roughly chopped) and partly chopped (discard the stalks).

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan then sprinkle on the rosemary and @plain flour{24%g}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato. Take your hot #baking tray{} out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Season with @salt{0.25%tsp}. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{45-50%minutes}, turn halfway through.

> TIP: If the potatoes are cooked before everything else is ready, turn your oven off and leave the potatoes on the bottom shelf to keep warm.

Meanwhile, season the @British beef roasting joint{450%g} with @salt{} and @pepper{} and transfer to a #roasting tray{}. Roast the beef on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{35-45-55%minutes} (depending on size) for medium rare. Add an extra ~{5%minutes} if you like your beef more cooked.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Once cooked, rest the beef wrapped loosely in #foil{} for at least ~{10%minutes} before slicing.

Peel the @celeriac{½}(peeled and chopped into 2cm chunks) and chop into 2cm chunks. Add the celeriac to the other pan of boiling water and simmer until tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> TIP: The celeriac is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Mix the @panko breadcrumbs{25%g} with a drizzle of @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Once cooked, drain in a colander, return to the pan and add the @reduced fat creme fraiche{150%g}, @crumbled blue cheese{30%g}. Pop onto medium heat, stir and cook until the creme fraiche has come to the boil, then remove from the heat. Season to taste. Pour into a small #oven dish{}, sprinkle over the breadcrumbs and bake in your oven until bubbling and slightly golden on top, ~{20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, put a medium sized #saucepan{} on medium high heat and add half the @unsalted butter{30%g}. Allow the butter to melt, then stir in the remaining flour to create a smooth paste. You've made a roux! Cook, stirring until the roux is a medium brown colour and gradually stir in the @water for the gravy{400%ml}, @red wine stock paste{28%g} and @redcurrant jelly{25%g}. Bring to the boil, carefully stirring out any lumps that form. Lower the heat and simmer until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{15-20%minutes}. Add a splash of water if necessary.

Pop one of your saucepans back on medium heat (no need to wash). Add the remaining butter, allow to melt then add the @chorizo{60%g}. Stir-fry until the chorizo is browned, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the @shredded savoy cabbage{150%g} and stir fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if you feel it needs it. Remove from the heat.

Once everything is ready (reheat the gravy and cabbage if you need to), thinly slice the beef and arrange on #plates{}. Serve the veggies and potatoes alongside. Add any beef resting juices or some water to the gravy to loosen it up if necessary, spoon over and enjoy!